# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: port-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The standard directly addresses an attack technique called Hardware Addition where an attacker posing as a guest, customer or staff smuggles a hacking device into the building that they then plug into the network giving them full access.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] A notable example of the issue occurred in 2005 when a machine attached to Walmart's network hacked thousands of their servers.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] IEEE 802.1X defines the encapsulation of the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) over wired IEEE 802 networks and over 802.11 wireless networks, which is known as "EAP over LAN" or EAPOL.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL was originally specified for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet, IEEE 802.5 Token Ring, and FDDI (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12 and ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2001, but was extended to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless in 802.1X-2004.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The EAPOL was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE ("MACsec") and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity, DevID) in 802.1X-2010 to support service identification and optional point to point encryption over the internal LAN segment.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X is part of the logical link control (LLC) sublayer of the 802 reference model.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X authentication involves three parties: a supplicant, an authenticator, and an authentication server.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The **supplicant** is a client device (such as a laptop) that wishes to attach to the LAN/WLAN.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The term 'supplicant' is also used interchangeably to refer to the software running on the client that provides credentials to the authenticator.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Authentication servers typically run software supporting the RADIUS and EAP protocols.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] In some cases, the authentication server software may be running on the authenticator hardware.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator acts like a security guard to a protected network.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant (i.e., client device) is not allowed access through the authenticator to the protected side of the network until the supplicant's identity has been validated and authorized.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] With 802.1X port-based authentication, the supplicant must initially provide the required credentials to the authenticator - these will have been specified in advance by the network administrator and could include a user name/password or a permitted digital certificate.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator forwards these credentials to the authentication server to decide whether access is to be granted.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] If the authentication server determines the credentials are valid, it informs the authenticator, which in turn allows the supplicant (client device) to access resources located on the protected side of the network.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL operates over the data link layer, and in Ethernet II framing protocol has an EtherType value of 0x888E.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2001 defines two logical port entities for an authenticated port—the "controlled port" and the "uncontrolled port".
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The controlled port is manipulated by the 802.1X PAE (Port Access Entity) to allow (in the authorized state) or prevent (in the unauthorized state) network traffic ingress and egress to/from the controlled port.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The uncontrolled port is used by the 802.1X PAE to transmit and receive EAPOL frames.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] 802.1X-2004 defines the equivalent port entities for the supplicant; so a supplicant implementing 802.1X-2004 may prevent higher-level protocols from being used if it is not content that authentication has successfully completed.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] This is particularly useful when an EAP method providing mutual authentication is used, as the supplicant can prevent data leakage when connected to an unauthorized network.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] **Initiation** To initiate authentication the authenticator will periodically transmit EAP-Request Identity frames to a special Layer 2 MAC address (*01:80:C2:00:00:03*) on the local network segment.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant listens at this address, and on receipt of the EAP-Request Identity frame, it responds with an EAP-Response Identity frame containing an identifier for the supplicant such as a User ID.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator then encapsulates this Identity response in a RADIUS Access-Request packet and forwards it on to the authentication server.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The supplicant may also initiate or restart authentication by sending an EAPOL-Start frame to the authenticator, which will then reply with an EAP-Request Identity frame.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] **Negotiation** *(Technically EAP negotiation)* The authentication server sends a reply (encapsulated in a RADIUS Access-Challenge packet) to the authenticator, containing an EAP Request specifying the EAP Method (The type of EAP based authentication it wishes the supplicant to perform).
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator encapsulates the EAP Request in an EAPOL frame and transmits it to the supplicant.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] At this point, the supplicant can start using the requested EAP Method, or do a NAK ("Negative Acknowledgement") and respond with the EAP Methods it is willing to perform.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] If authentication is successful, the authenticator sets the port to the "authorized" state and normal traffic is allowed.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] If it is unsuccessful, the port remains in the "unauthorized" state.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] When the supplicant logs off, it sends an EAPOL-logoff message to the authenticator, the authenticator then sets the port to the "unauthorized" state, once again blocking all non-EAP traffic.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] An open-source project named Open1X produces a client, Xsupplicant.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] This client is currently available for both Linux and Windows.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The main drawbacks of the Open1X client are that it does not provide comprehensible and extensive user documentation and that most Linux vendors do not provide a package for it.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The more general wpa_supplicant can be used for 802.11 wireless networks and wired networks.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Both support a very wide range of EAP types.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] ChromeOS has supported 802.1X since mid-2011.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Avenda Systems provides a supplicant for Windows, Linux and macOS.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] They also have a plugin for the Microsoft NAP framework.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Avenda also offers health checking agents.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows defaults to not responding to 802.1X authentication requests for 20 minutes after a failed authentication.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] This can cause significant disruption to clients.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The block period can be configured using the HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\dot3svc\BlockTime DWORD value (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\wlansvc\BlockTime for wireless networks) in the registry (entered in minutes).
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] A hotfix is required for Windows XP SP3 and Windows Vista SP2 to make the period configurable.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Wildcard server certificates are not supported by EAPHost, the Windows component that provides EAP support in the operating system.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The implication of this is that when using a commercial certification authority, individual certificates must be purchased.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows XP has major issues with its handling of IP address changes resulting from user-based 802.1X authentication that changes the VLAN and thus subnet of clients.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Microsoft has stated that it will not backport the SSO feature from Vista that resolves these issues.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] If users are not logging in with roaming profiles, a hotfix must be downloaded and installed if authenticating via PEAP with PEAP-MSCHAPv2.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows Vista-based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, as a result, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 based computers that are connected via an IP phone may not authenticate as expected and, consequently, the client can be placed into the wrong VLAN.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows 7 does not respond to 802.1X authentication requests after initial 802.1X authentication fails.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Windows PE does not have native support for 802.1X.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] However, support can be added to WinPE 2.1 and WinPE 3.0 through hotfixes that are available from Microsoft.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Although full documentation is not yet available, preliminary documentation for the use of these hotfixes is available via a Microsoft blog.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Most Linux distributions support 802.1X via wpa_supplicant and desktop integration like NetworkManager.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The iPhone and iPod Touch support 802.1X since the release of iOS 2.0. macOS has offered native support since Mac OS X Panther.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] As of iOS 17 and macOS 14, Apple devices support connecting to 802.1X networks using EAP-TLS with TLS 1.3 (EAP-TLS 1.3).
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Additionally, devices running iOS/iPadOS/tvOS 17 or later support wired 802.1X networks.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Android has support for 802.1X since the release of 1.6 Donut.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] eduroam (the international roaming service), mandates the use of 802.1X authentication when providing network access to guests visiting from other eduroam-enabled institutions.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] BT (British Telecom, PLC) employs Identity Federation for authentication in services delivered to a wide variety of industries and governments.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Not all devices support 802.1X authentication.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Examples include network printers, Ethernet-based electronics like environmental sensors, cameras, and wireless phones.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] For those devices to be used in a protected network environment, alternative mechanisms must be provided to authenticate them.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] One option would be to disable 802.1X on that port, but that leaves that port unprotected and open for abuse.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Another slightly more reliable option is to use the MAB option.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] When MAB is configured on a port, that port will first try to check if the connected device is 802.1X compliant, and if no reaction is received from the connected device, it will try to authenticate with the AAA server using the connected device's MAC address as username and password.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The network administrator then must make provisions on the RADIUS server to authenticate those MAC addresses, either by adding them as regular users or implementing additional logic to resolve them in a network inventory database.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Many managed Ethernet switches offer options for this.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] In the summer of 2005, Microsoft's Steve Riley posted an article (based on the original research of Microsoft MVP Svyatoslav Pidgorny) detailing a serious vulnerability in the 802.1X protocol, involving a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] Riley suggests that for wired networks the use of IPsec or a combination of IPsec and 802.1X would be more secure.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] EAPOL-Logoff frames transmitted by the 802.1X supplicant are sent in the clear and contain no data derived from the credential exchange that initially authenticated the client.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] They are therefore trivially easy to spoof on shared media and can be used as part of a targeted DoS on both wired and wireless LANs.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] In an EAPOL-Logoff attack, a malicious third party with access to the medium the authenticator is attached to repeatedly sends forged EAPOL-Logoff frames from the target device's MAC Address.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The authenticator (believing that the targeted device wishes to end its authentication session) closes the target's authentication session, blocking traffic ingressing from the target, denying it access to the network.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The 802.1X-2010 specification, which began as 802.1af, addresses vulnerabilities in previous 802.1X specifications, by using MACsec IEEE 802.1AE to encrypt data between logical ports (running on top of a physical port) and IEEE 802.1AR (Secure Device Identity / DevID) authenticated devices.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] As a stopgap, until these enhancements are widely implemented, some vendors have extended the 802.1X-2001 and 802.1X-2004 protocol, allowing multiple concurrent authentication sessions to occur on a single port.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] While this prevents traffic from devices with unauthenticated MAC addresses ingressing on an 802.1X authenticated port, it will not stop a malicious device snooping on traffic from an authenticated device and provides no protection against MAC spoofing, or EAPOL-Logoff attacks.
[src:port-security/ieee-802-1x] The IETF-backed alternative is the Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA), which also carries EAP, although it works at layer 3, using UDP, thus not being tied to the 802 infrastructure.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] In IEEE 802 LAN/MAN standards, the **medium access control** (**MAC**), also called **media access control**, is the layer that controls the hardware responsible for interaction with the wired (electrical or optical) or wireless transmission medium.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The MAC sublayer and the logical link control (LLC) sublayer together make up the data link layer.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The LLC provides flow control and multiplexing for the logical link (i.e.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] EtherType, 802.1Q VLAN tag etc), while the MAC provides flow control and multiplexing for the transmission medium.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] These two sublayers together correspond to layer 2 of the OSI model.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] For compatibility reasons, LLC is optional for implementations of IEEE 802.3 (the frames are then "raw"), but compulsory for implementations of other IEEE 802 physical layer standards.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Within the hierarchy of the OSI model and IEEE 802 standards, the MAC sublayer provides a control abstraction of the physical layer such that the complexities of physical link control are invisible to the LLC and upper layers of the network stack.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Thus, any LLC sublayer (and higher layers) may be used with any MAC.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] In turn, the medium access control block is formally connected to the PHY via a media-independent interface.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Although the MAC block is today typically integrated with the PHY within the same device package, historically any MAC could be used with any PHY, independent of the transmission medium.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] For topologies with a collision domain (bus, ring, mesh, point-to-multipoint topologies), the channel access method controls when data is sent and when waiting is necessary to avoid collisions.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Additionally, the MAC is also responsible for compensating for collisions by initiating retransmission if a jam signal is detected.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] When receiving data from the physical layer, the MAC block ensures data integrity by verifying the sender's frame check sequences and strips off the sender's preamble and padding before passing the data up to the higher layers.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The local network addresses used in IEEE 802 networks and FDDI networks are called *MAC addresses*; they are based on the addressing scheme that was used in early Ethernet implementations.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] A MAC address is intended as a unique serial number.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] MAC addresses are typically assigned to network interface hardware at the time of manufacture.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The most significant part of the address identifies the manufacturer, who assigns the remainder of the address, thus providing a potentially unique address.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] This makes it possible for frames to be delivered on a network link that interconnects hosts by some combination of repeaters, hubs, bridges and switches, but not by network layer routers.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Examples of physical networks are Ethernet networks and Wi-Fi networks, both of which are IEEE 802 networks and use IEEE 802 48-bit MAC addresses.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] A MAC layer is not required in full-duplex point-to-point communication, but address fields are included in some point-to-point protocols for compatibility reasons.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanisms provided by the MAC layer are also known as a multiple access method.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] This makes it possible for several stations connected to the same physical medium to share it.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Examples of shared physical media are bus networks, ring networks, hub networks, wireless networks and half-duplex point-to-point links.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The multiple access method may detect or avoid data packet collisions if a packet mode contention based channel access method is used, or reserve resources to establish a logical channel if a circuit-switched or channelization-based channel access method is used.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The channel access control mechanism relies on a physical layer multiplex scheme.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The most widespread multiple access method is the contention-based CSMA/CD used in Ethernet networks.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] This mechanism is only utilized within a network collision domain, for example, an Ethernet bus network or a hub-based star topology network.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] An Ethernet network may be divided into several collision domains, interconnected by bridges and switches.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] A multiple access method is not required in a switched full-duplex network, such as today's switched Ethernet networks, but is often available in the equipment for compatibility reasons.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Use of directional antennas and millimeter-wave communication in a wireless personal area network increases the probability of concurrent scheduling of non‐interfering transmissions in a localized area, which results in an immense increase in network throughput.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] However, the optimum scheduling of concurrent transmission is an NP-hard problem.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] Cellular networks, such as GSM, UMTS or LTE networks, also use a MAC layer.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The MAC protocol in cellular networks is designed to maximize the utilization of the expensive licensed spectrum.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The air interface of a cellular network is at layers 1 and 2 of the OSI model; at layer 2, it is divided into multiple protocol layers.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] In UMTS and LTE, those protocols are the Packet Data Convergence Protocol (PDCP), the Radio Link Control (RLC) protocol, and the MAC protocol.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The base station has absolute control over the air interface and schedules the downlink access as well as the uplink access of all devices.
[src:port-security/media-access-control] The MAC protocol is specified by 3GPP in TS 25.321 for UMTS, TS 36.321 for LTE and TS 38.321 for 5G.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Network access control is a computer networking solution that uses a set of protocols to define and implement a policy that describes how to secure access to network nodes by devices when they initially attempt to access the network.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A basic form of NAC is the 802.1X standard.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Network access control aims to do exactly what the name implies—control access to a network with policies, including pre-admission endpoint security policy checks and post-admission controls over where users and devices can go on a network and what they can do.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] When a computer connects to a computer network, it is not permitted to access anything unless it complies with a business defined policy; including anti-virus protection level, system update level and configuration.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] While the computer is being checked by a pre-installed software agent, it can only access resources that can remediate (resolve or update) any issues.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Once the policy is met, the computer is able to access network resources and the Internet, within the policies defined by the NAC system.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] NAC is mainly used for endpoint health checks, but it is often tied to Role-based Access.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Access to the network will be given according to the profile of the person and the results of a posture/health check.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] For example, in an enterprise the HR department could access only HR department files if both the role and the endpoint meets anti-virus minimums.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] NAC is an emerging security product category, whose definition is both evolving and controversial.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] There are two prevailing designs in NAC, based on whether policies are enforced before or after end-stations gain access to the network.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] In the former case, called **pre-admission** NAC, end-stations are inspected prior to being allowed on the network.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A typical use case of pre-admission NAC would be to prevent clients with out-of-date antivirus signatures from talking to sensitive servers.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Alternatively, **post-admission** NAC makes enforcement decisions based on user actions, after those users have been provided with access to the network.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] The fundamental idea behind NAC is to allow the network to make access control decisions based on intelligence about end-systems, so the manner in which the network is informed about end-systems is a key design decision.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A key difference among NAC systems is whether they require agent software to report end-system characteristics, or whether they use scanning and network inventory techniques to discern those characteristics remotely.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] As NAC has matured, software developers such as Microsoft have adopted the approach, providing their network access protection (NAP) agent as part of their Windows 7, Vista and XP releases, however, beginning with Windows 10, Microsoft no longer supports NAP.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] There are also NAP compatible agents for Linux and Mac OS X that provide equal intelligence for these operating systems.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] In some out-of-band systems, agents are distributed on end-stations and report information to a central console, which in turn can control switches to enforce policy.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] In contrast the inline solutions can be single-box solutions which act as internal firewalls for access-layer networks and enforce the policy.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Out-of-band solutions have the advantage of reusing existing infrastructure; inline products can be easier to deploy on new networks, and may provide more advanced network enforcement capabilities, because they are directly in control of individual packets on the wire.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] However, there are products that are agentless, and have both the inherent advantages of easier, less risky out-of-band deployment, but use techniques to provide inline effectiveness for non-compliant devices, where enforcement is required.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Network operators deploy NAC products with the expectation that some legitimate clients will be denied access to the network (if users never had out-of-date patch levels, NAC would be unnecessary).
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Because of this, NAC solutions require a mechanism to remediate the end-user problems that deny them access.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A quarantine network is a restricted IP network that provides users with routed access only to certain hosts and applications.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] assignment; when a NAC product determines that an end-user is out-of-date, their switch port is assigned to a VLAN that is routed only to patch and update servers, not to the rest of the network.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] (NDP)) for quarantine, avoiding the overhead of managing quarantine VLANs.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] that provides instructions and tools for updating their computer.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Until their computer passes automated inspection, no network usage besides the captive portal is allowed.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] This is similar to the way paid wireless access works at public access points.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] External Captive Portals allow organizations to offload wireless controllers and switches from hosting web portals.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A single external portal hosted by a NAC appliance for wireless and wired authentication eliminates the need to create multiple portals, and consolidates policy management processes.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Using NAC in a mobile deployment, where workers connect over various wireless networks throughout the workday, involves challenges that are not present in a wired LAN environment.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] When a user is denied access because of a security concern, productive use of the device is lost, which can impact the ability to complete a job or serve a customer.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] In addition, automated remediation that takes only seconds on a wired connection may take minutes over a slower wireless data connection, bogging down the device.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A mobile NAC solution gives system administrators greater control over whether, when and how to remediate the security concern.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] A lower-grade concern such as out-of-date antivirus signatures may result in a simple warning to the user, while more serious issues may result in quarantining the device.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] Policies may be set so that automated remediation, such as pushing out and applying security patches and updates, is withheld until the device is connected over a Wi-Fi or faster connection, or after working hours.
[src:port-security/network-access-control] This allows administrators to most appropriately balance the need for security against the goal of keeping workers productive.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:port-security/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:port-security/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:port-security/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:port-security/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:port-security/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:port-security/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:port-security/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:port-security/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:port-security/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:port-security/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:port-security/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:port-security/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:port-security/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:port-security/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:port-security/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:port-security/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:port-security/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:port-security/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:port-security/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:port-security/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:port-security/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:port-security/port-security] Internationally, port security is governed by rules issued by the International Maritime Organization and its 2002 International Ship and Port Facility Security Code.
[src:port-security/port-security] Additionally, some United States–based programs have become *de facto* global port security programs, including the Container Security Initiative and the Customs Trade Partnership against Terrorism.
[src:port-security/port-security] However, some businesses argue that port security governance measures are ineffective and costly and that it negatively impacts maritime transport costs.
[src:port-security/port-security] Physical port security involves the risks to the perimeters of the port.
[src:port-security/port-security] Risks to port security involves natural risks such as hurricanes and flooding, man-made risks such as operator error, and weapon risks such as chemical, biological and nuclear material.
[src:port-security/port-security] It also involves adequate security systems within the port, such as security guards, video surveillance and alarm systems.
[src:port-security/port-security] Physical port security also falls under the umbrella of maritime terrorism.
[src:port-security/port-security] Ports are attractive targets for terrorists because ships and cargoes are fixed in time once they enter the port, which removes the uncertainty in relation to the location of the target.
[src:port-security/port-security] Apart from physical port security, the port is connected to a larger supply chain.
[src:port-security/port-security] There are various risks along this supply chain that can affect port security, such as explosives attached to the vessel or unwanted passengers on the vessel.
[src:port-security/port-security] Ports are "potential targets of illegal activity which may impact their ability to function as intended, and ports as conduits into and out of national borders and supply chains, which can be exploited in order to introduce or move illegal materials, persons, or activities".
[src:port-security/port-security] That involves increasing the number of vulnerabilities to port security to the supply chain.
[src:port-security/port-security] Security risk management practices of ports reflect the goal of preparing for the inevitable nature of risk before an event occurs.
[src:port-security/port-security] Examples of security risk management practices at ports are: employment of a security director, crisis leadership, contingency planning and the use of intelligence.
[src:port-security/port-security] Other measures include physical security barriers, such as CCTV cameras and adequate light at the port in order to ensure that cargo theft does not take place.
[src:port-security/port-security] Examples of risk management practices within the maritime supply chain include ISPC (International Ship and Port Facility Security Code), CSI (Container Security Initiative) and whole-of-supply chain outcomes, CTPT (Customs-Trade Partnership Against Terrorism).
[src:port-security/port-security] These efforts have been criticised as the use of quantitative and statistical approach to security in the maritime supply chain is argued to overlook low probability, high impact events.
[src:port-security/port-security] Examples of cyberspace security risk management practices of ports are: investment in cyber defense mechanisms for port infrastructure, cybersecurity awareness and training programs.
[src:port-security/port-security] These programs educate employees about cyber risks, to help prevent and to mitigate potential cyber threats.
[src:port-security/port-security] Other measures include collaboration and information sharing.
[src:port-security/port-security] Collaboration with other relevant actors in the maritime sector can help ports stay well informed about global cyber threats, which in turn can help preemptively to address emerging cyber threats.
[src:port-security/port-security] Port security is often in the literature depicted as a responsibility of the state, as it concerns national security.
[src:port-security/port-security] Yet, the emergence of private security actors has also influenced aspects of port security governance.
[src:port-security/port-security] In the case of a port in Indonesian, the involvement of so many different types of state and non- state agencies actually lessened security.
[src:port-security/port-security] Maritime security is undergoing rapid digitalization and technological advancements, leading to an increased reliance on onshore infrastructure to support critical maritime operations.
[src:port-security/port-security] The increased connectivity and digitization of services in the maritime industry has impacted the risk of cyber attacks and threats in several ways.
[src:port-security/port-security] It has expanded the attack surface, created new threats, created a hostile threat environment, and increased vulnerabilities onshore.
[src:port-security/port-security] Maritime cyber risks include attacks on ports and port systems.
[src:port-security/port-security] Attacks such as malware insertion, including cyber and ransomware attacks.
[src:port-security/port-security] In these attacks, cyber criminals encrypt computers and networks within the onshore infrastructure, demanding a ransom in exchange for decryption.
[src:port-security/port-security] Other cyber risks include Business Email Compromise Fraud.
[src:port-security/port-security] In this instance, cyber criminals trick employees into wiring them money to a foreign account.
[src:port-security/port-security] In reality, the account belongs to the cyber criminals, which they will gain monetary benefits from.
[src:port-security/port-security] Foreign state espionage in the maritime sector is another cyber risk, threatening port security.
[src:port-security/port-security] It involves hackers employed by states to conduct cyber espionage.
[src:port-security/port-security] What the state hackers will gain from espionage is an insight into onshore facilities, like ports.
[src:port-security/port-security] Their intentions are strategic, aiming to acquire foreign technology, possibly to develop the cyber criminals’ destructive cyber attack capacity.
[src:port-security/port-security] Another cyber risk ports are faced with is hackers that are compromising IT systems on board of ships, allowing the cyber criminals to gain an insight into, for an example, the ship’s location and cargo.
[src:port-security/port-security] Ports use a variety of sensors, such as Wi- Fi and satellite-based Internet systems which are increasingly automated.
[src:port-security/port-security] Such systems are vulnerable to penetration and manipulation and risk being misused for hacktivism and by terrorists.
[src:port-security/port-security] Not only can this affect port security in terms of the parameters of the surface of the port, but a possible hacking of data can be used to trace ships and mislead them for hijacking purposes.
[src:port-security/port-security] Technological developments coupled with the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Shale Revolution has allowed for increasing exports of liquefied natural gas (LNG).
[src:port-security/port-security] The commodity, consisting of 70-90 percent methane and 0-20 percent of butane, propane and ethane is similar to crude oil as it forms through pressurising and heating.
[src:port-security/port-security] LNG derives at onshore or offshore ports, where the infrastructure at the port contains terminals that bring the LNG further.
[src:port-security/port-security] It can either be attached to a gas liqufication or storage plant, a regasification and storage plant or just a storage and distribution plant.
[src:port-security/port-security] The infrastructure at LNG terminals are therefore concerned with highly flammable content that is of security risk to personnel.
[src:port-security/port-security] Onshore LNG ports that are located close to cities or dense populations are also a security risk to the area surrounding the port.
[src:port-security/port-security] Risks to port security will vary considerably and depend on the waiting position of a tanker, location of the port, and security risk management practices of each specific port.
[src:port-security/port-security] LNG is naturally linked to maritime terrorism, as disputed areas and chokepoints -such as the Strait of Malacca and Singapore Strait- has the potential to result in hijacking and bombs as the area becomes more active.
[src:port-security/port-security] As the new demand centres for LNG is most notably in Asian countries such as China, India, Japan and South Korea, new geopolitical tensions might increase in the region between LNG- exporting countries such as the U.S., Russia and Qatar.
[src:port-security/port-security] This also relates to energy security, as import dependent countries are vulnerable to a sudden stop in supply of LNG.
[src:port-security/port-security] Following the September 11 Attacks, the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Government acknowledged the threat of unsecured ports and shipping containers.
[src:port-security/port-security] By 2001, the U.S. economy was already heavily reliant on maritime shipping, and that reliance was set to double by 2020.
[src:port-security/port-security] Coast Guard officer Stephen Flynn has stated that interest in shipping container security has seen a definitive shift pre and post-9/11.
[src:port-security/port-security] Shipping container and port security pre-9/11 was focused primarily on promoting the advancement of globalization.
[src:port-security/port-security] These interests were prioritised over sea and border defence.
[src:port-security/port-security] Customs and Border Protection was more focused on combating drug smuggling.
[src:port-security/port-security] The maritime suicide bombing carried out against the USS Cole in October 2000 by Al-Qaeda illustrated the probability of future maritime based terrorist attacks against the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] In response, terrorist groups such as Al-Qaeda were flagged as the largest threat to maritime supply chains; as their maritime skills were rapidly improving and U.S. maritime security regimes remained weak.
[src:port-security/port-security] However, post-9/11, the U.S. government realized the risks and threats associated with unsecured maritime transport - particularly the containerised transport of nuclear material into U.S. ports.
[src:port-security/port-security] Additionally, the U.S. government showed an interest in funding and developing homeland security, which has been critiqued by maritime experts as merely ‘constructing barricades to fend off terrorists’.
[src:port-security/port-security] In the years since, academics have called for the creation of an international security regime that allows the U.S. ‘to remain an open, prosperous, free and globally engaged society’ as more than 6000 international vessels and 100,000 seafarers visit U.S. ports every year.
[src:port-security/port-security] Every year, the United States Marine Transportation System moves more than 2 billion tons of domestic and international goods.
[src:port-security/port-security] It imports 3.3 billion tons of domestic oil, transports 134 million passengers by ferry, serves the 78 million Americans engaged in recreational boating and hosts more than 5 million cruise ship passengers a year.
[src:port-security/port-security] Although shipping containers have been widely used since World War II, in 2002 it was estimated that less than 3% of the 20 million containers that entered U.S. ports were scanned or inspected.
[src:port-security/port-security] This statistic is made clearer when understood in the context of the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Customs and Border Protection’s protocol.
[src:port-security/port-security] At Port Newark-Elizabeth Marine Terminal, 82% of the product passing through is "trusted" by the Customs agents as routine activity.
[src:port-security/port-security] Only 18% of the shipments are an "anomaly" to the known shipments.
[src:port-security/port-security] This, in addition to the requirements for shippers to provide cargo lists, explains the reasoning behind such low search figures.
[src:port-security/port-security] In 2001, the Port and Maritime Security Act of 2001 was submitted to the House of Representatives, and subsequently referred to the Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation.
[src:port-security/port-security] Some changes were made to the bill, however it was passed into law in 2002 as the Maritime Transportation Security Act of 2002.
[src:port-security/port-security] Many of the provisions within the Maritime Transportation Security Act of 2002 call for additional attention to be paid to seaports as potential targets of terrorist attacks, and the coordination of the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Coast Guard and government agencies to update their maritime counter terrorism plans.
[src:port-security/port-security] Some of the points include directives to develop anti-terrorism cargo identification tracking, improved screening systems to be used on containers being shipped to the U.S. from foreign ports and enhanced physical security of shipping containers including updates standards on seals and locks.
[src:port-security/port-security] Additionally, federal security standardizations were set for the first time regarding restrictions to specific areas, surveillance measures and developing security plans.
[src:port-security/port-security] In the 2005 109th Session of Congress, the most maritime security related bills were introduced since 9/11, showing a significant increase in interest in these issues among federal officials.
[src:port-security/port-security] All 7 bills, however, died in either the House of Representatives or the Senate.
[src:port-security/port-security] The period following 9/11 demonstrates a broadening of security initiatives and focus on terrorist capabilities.
[src:port-security/port-security] Coast Guard officer John Harrald states that while there has been significant growth in container surveillance interest and initiatives from 2001 to 2005, in comparison to the growth of conventional national security and aviation security it is ‘dwarfed’.
[src:port-security/port-security] In 2001, the Customs-Trade Partnership Against Terrorism (CTPAT) was created in an attempt to bolster the Bush Administration's post-9/11 multi-layered cargo enforcement strategy.
[src:port-security/port-security] The initiative is a voluntary partnership between principal stakeholders in the public and private sector (importers, shipping container carriers, customs brokers and manufacturers).
[src:port-security/port-security] A year later, in 2002, the Container Security Initiative (CSI) was launched by the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Specifically focusing on containerised cargo entering U.S. ports, the bilateral information sharing initiative was intended to ‘extend the zone of security outward so that American borders are the last line of defence, not the first’.
[src:port-security/port-security] The reciprocal system between U.S. and foreign ports, makes it possible for U.S. bound shipping containers to be inspected at their host port, instead of upon arrival in the U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] The 2002 RAND SeaCurity conference revealed that the European Commission ‘strongly opposes’ the Container Security Initiative (CSI) and particularly the Customs-Trade Partnership Against Terrorism (CTPAT).
[src:port-security/port-security] One reason given was that the shipping container's safety seal is only required to be placed on its doors at the port of departure, not the port of origin.
[src:port-security/port-security] Therefore, the container is unsealed and exposed through most of its journey through international ports.
[src:port-security/port-security] The United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) was established in 1997, however expanded after 9/11 to include maritime crime and piracy.
[src:port-security/port-security] In 2015, the UNODC released the first annual report on their Global Maritime Crime Programme.
[src:port-security/port-security] The programme assists 18 countries in combating ‘the smuggling of migrants and people trafficking, wildlife and forestry crime, piracy and armed robbery, Somali charcoal smuggling, fisheries crime and the growing threat of narcotics trafficking on the high seas of the Indian Ocean’.
[src:port-security/port-security] However, neither the UNODC's annual reports, nor their Maritime Crime Manual for Criminal Justice Practitioners, make any mention of shipping container surveillance.
[src:port-security/port-security] The International Ship and Port Facility Security Code (ISPS) is an amendment of the Safety of Life at Sea Convention (SOLAS), which entered into force in July 2004.
[src:port-security/port-security] The code provides a security regime for international shipping and port security.
[src:port-security/port-security] Compliance is mandatory for the 148 contracting parties to SOLAS, however there are no consequences for non-compliance.
[src:port-security/port-security] ISPS is therefore a security framework for states, whereby 'each ship and each port facility will have to determine the measures needed to intensify its security measures to appropriately offset the threat by reducing its vulnerability.
[src:port-security/port-security] Chalk, however, is quick to point out that even by 2008, government initiatives were still limited in scope.
[src:port-security/port-security] Criticising the International Ship and Port Facility Security Code as a failure, since it includes countries who lack resources to properly comply and audit.
[src:port-security/port-security] Leaving many ports conducting "tick in the box" security verification procedures on container shipments which will eventually arrive in U.S. ports.
[src:port-security/port-security] Stating the U.S. must begin by working with like minded allies internationally.
[src:port-security/port-security] The result has been the collection of programs which overlap, interact and leave significant gaps.
[src:port-security/port-security] The overall effectiveness of national and international efforts is impossible to assess’.
