[src:port-security/port-security] Admiral James Loy and Captain Robert Ross suggest a multilateral approach with U.S. trading partners (public and private) be pursued.
[src:port-security/port-security] Coast Guard Commander Stephen Flynn also suggests extending current initiatives to include bilateral and multilateral international inspection zones.
[src:port-security/port-security] European stakeholders take a similar position to Loy, Ross and Flynn, encouraging the inclusion of the private sector in any counter-measure actions taken by the government, so as to avoid ‘affect container throughput – affecting the commercial imperative’.
[src:port-security/port-security] The importance of the container shipping industry is equally matched by its vulnerabilities to terrorist attack.
[src:port-security/port-security] The U.S. maritime system consists of over 300 sea and river ports with more than 3,700 cargo and passenger terminals.
[src:port-security/port-security] The United States and global economies depend on commercial shipping as the most reliable, cost efficient method of transporting goods, with U.S. ports handling approximately 20% of the maritime trade worldwide.
[src:port-security/port-security] The volume of trade throughout the U.S. and the world creates a desirable target for terrorist attack.
[src:port-security/port-security] An attack on any aspect of the maritime system, mainly major ports, can severely hamper trade and potentially affect the global economy by billions of dollars.
[src:port-security/port-security] The security of ports and their deficiencies are numerous and leave U.S. ports vulnerable to terrorist attack.
[src:port-security/port-security] The vulnerabilities of our ports are many, leading to potential security breaches in almost all aspects of the container shipping industry.
[src:port-security/port-security] With the sheer volume of maritime traffic, there is serious concern of cargo/passenger ship hijackings and pirate attack, as well as accountability of the millions of shipping containers transported worldwide.
[src:port-security/port-security] Given the overwhelming number of ships and containers, there are many areas of concern regarding the security of U.S. ports.
[src:port-security/port-security] Terrorists can, and eventually may, exploit the shipping industry's deficiencies in port security.
[src:port-security/port-security] Potential threats include the smuggling of weapons of mass destruction (WMD), a radiological "dirty" bomb, a conventional explosive device, and transportation of terrorist operatives, as well.
[src:port-security/port-security] Studies have claimed a Hiroshima sized nuclear detonation at a major seaport would kill fifty thousand to one million people.
[src:port-security/port-security] It is common knowledge within the industry that security measures of major ports cannot have a significant effect on the movement of goods, thereby allowing exploitation of the system for terrorist use.
[src:port-security/port-security] The geographical/physical layout of the ports themselves is of concern.
[src:port-security/port-security] The protection and security of the landside perimeter of a port is difficult due to their large size.
[src:port-security/port-security] Ports located in highly urbanized areas allow terrorists a densely populated area in which to hide while infiltrating or escaping the port area at their perimeter.
[src:port-security/port-security] The high volume of trucks entering and exiting port facilities pose a threat to the port, as well as surrounding geographical areas.
[src:port-security/port-security] Exiting trucks may contain WMD or terrorist operatives that are to infiltrate a surrounding metropolitan area, i.e., transporting a chemical explosive device (from the Port of Los Angeles) to a more densely populated area (downtown Los Angeles).
[src:port-security/port-security] Container ships anchored at port facilities are particularly vulnerable to both highjacking and explosive devices as they are stationary targets.
[src:port-security/port-security] Most crews of cargo ships are unarmed, and would be defenseless to an armed attack.
[src:port-security/port-security] The disabling of a ship at port is enough to halt all activity at that port for an extended period of time, especially if the disabled ship is blocking a throughway for other vessels.
[src:port-security/port-security] The economic impact of such an attack would be disastrous on a global scale.
[src:port-security/port-security] An example of such an economic impact can be drawn from a labor-management dispute that closed ports along the west coast of the United States.
[src:port-security/port-security] These port closures cost the U.S. economy approximately $1 billion per day for the first 5 days, and rose exponentially thereafter.
[src:port-security/port-security] When the International Longshore and Warehouse Union strike closed 29 West Coast ports for 10 days, one study estimated that it cost the United States economy $19.4 billion.
[src:port-security/port-security] Many manufacturing companies of the world employ a just-in-time distribution model, allowing for lower inventory carrying costs and savings from warehouse space.
[src:port-security/port-security] The shipping industry is essential to this method, as its speed and reliability allow new inventory to be shipped and received precisely when it is needed.
[src:port-security/port-security] The adopting of the just-in-time method has dropped business logistics cost from 16.1% of U.S.
[src:port-security/port-security] Although this method has dropped costs significantly, it has put a stranglehold on security options, as the shipping times of these shipments are exact and cannot afford delays from inspection.
[src:port-security/port-security] Other aspects of economic impact include costs of altering shipping routes away from a disabled port, as well as delays from ports operating over capacity that receive the rerouted ships.
[src:port-security/port-security] Most ports operate at near capacity and can ill afford an attack of this nature.
[src:port-security/port-security] Although there are many government sponsored agencies involved with port security, the responsibility of providing that security is of state and local governments.
[src:port-security/port-security] Allen (2007) states that 'under the protective principle, a state has jurisdiction to prescribe and enforce laws against acts that threaten vital state interests'.
[src:port-security/port-security] The protective principle 'recognizes that a state may apply its laws to protect vital state interests, such as the state's national security or governmental functions'.
[src:port-security/port-security] Some ports may enact their own police forces in addition to city law enforcement.
[src:port-security/port-security] There have been proposals to consolidate federal agencies responsible for border security.
[src:port-security/port-security] The consolidation may offer some long-term benefits, but three challenges may hinder a successful implementation of security enhancing initiatives at the nations ports: standards, funding, and collaboration.
[src:port-security/port-security] The first challenge involves implementing a set of standards that defines what safeguards a port should have in place.
[src:port-security/port-security] Under the Coast Guard's direction, a set of standards is being developed for all U.S. ports to use in conducting port vulnerability assessments.
[src:port-security/port-security] However, many questions remain about whether the thousands of people who have grown accustomed to working in certain ways at the nation's ports will agree to, and implement, the kinds of changes that a substantially changed environment will require.
[src:port-security/port-security] The second challenge involves determining the amounts needed and sources of funding for the kinds of security improvements that are likely to be required to meet the standards.
[src:port-security/port-security] Florida's experience indicates that security measures are likely to be more expensive than many anticipate, and determining how to pay these costs and how the federal government should participate will present a challenge.
[src:port-security/port-security] The third challenge is ensuring that there is sufficient cooperation and coordination among the many stakeholders to make the security measures work.
[src:port-security/port-security] Experience to date indicates that this coordination is more difficult than many stakeholders anticipate, and that continued practice and testing will be key in making it work.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:port-security/virtual-lan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
